sec.p:
The jvenn library accepts three different input formats : “Lists”, “Intersection counts” and “Count lists”. Examples are presented in Table 2, where the different lists are “sample1” and “sample2”, the elements of the different lists are given in the fields “data”. For “Intersection counts”, the lists are given a label (“A” or “B”) which is used to make the correspondence between the list and its count. Finally, “Count lists” provide a count number for each element of a list. Hence, with “Count lists” the figures presented in the diagram correspond to the sums of counts of all elements shared between lists. they can be particularly useful to present OTU read counts [11]. For “Lists” and “Count lists”, jvenn computes the intersection counts and displays the chart. For “intersection counts”, the intersection counts is provided by the user.Table 2

Available input formats

FormatExample

series: [{


name: ’sample1’,


data: [~Otu1~, ~Otu2~, ~Otu3~, ~Otu4~, ~Otu5~, ~Otu6~, ~Otu7~]

